<subSubSection id="81B6651AFFEFFFE94D81FD8CFE1A9196" pageId="8" pageNumber="588" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C9133691FFEFFFE94D81FD8CFE1A9196" blockId="8.[151,1437,151,789]" pageId="8" pageNumber="588">
<emphasis id="FBD8EA83FFEFFFE94D81FD8CFEEE9106" bold="true" box="[199,317,583,608]" pageId="8" pageNumber="588">Remarks:</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="0EAC4D12FFEFFFE94F18FD82FBFE9106" authority="Rao &amp; Ramakrishnan, 1990" authorityName="Rao &amp; Ramakrishnan" authorityYear="1990" box="[606,1069,583,608]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hecalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="morrisoni">
<emphasis id="FBD8EA83FFEFFFE94F18FD82FD3D9139" box="[606,750,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="588">H. morrisoni</emphasis>
Rao &amp; Ramakrishnan, 
<quantity id="0E549B74FFEFFFE94EB3FD83FBFE9106" box="[1013,1069,584,608]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0546" pageId="8" pageNumber="588" unit="in" value="1990.0">1990</quantity>
</taxonomicName>
in having the pygofer lobe acute apically and the leaf-like aedeagal processes directed cephalad. But it differs in having the much straighter aedeagal shaft without median constriction and few serrations above median length. Male genitalia are also much closer to 
<taxonomicName id="0EAC4D12FFEFFFE94C42FD7EFDB291AA" authority="Distant, 1908" authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1908" box="[260,609,692,717]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hecalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="umballaensis">
<emphasis id="FBD8EA83FFEFFFE94C42FD7EFE6F91AA" box="[260,444,692,716]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="588">H. umballaensis</emphasis>
Distant, 1908
</taxonomicName>
but the pygofer lobe is acute in this new species and aedeagal shaft is without apical constriction.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="81B6651AFFEFFFE94D81FD37FB7F9073" box="[199,1196,764,789]" pageId="8" pageNumber="588" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="C9133691FFEFFFE94D81FD37FB7F9073" blockId="8.[151,1437,151,789]" box="[199,1196,764,789]" pageId="8" pageNumber="588">
<emphasis id="FBD8EA83FFEFFFE94D81FD37FE829073" bold="true" box="[199,337,764,789]" pageId="8" pageNumber="588">Etymology:</emphasis>
The species epithet refers to the straight aedeagal shaft without constriction.
</paragraph>
